pretive approaches: "therapeutic reading" (premised on the assurance that literary confrontations with historical trauma will enable psychic healing in the present), and "prohibitive reading" (anchored in the belief that fictions of returning to the past are dangerous and to be avoided). Levy-Hussen argues that these norms have become overly restrictive, standing in the way of a more supple method of interpretation that recognizes and attends to the indirect, unexpected, inconsistent, and opaque workings of historical fantasy and desire. Moving beyond the question of whether literature must heal or abandon historical wounds, Levy-Hussen proposes new ways to read African American literature now.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAfrican American artsxInfluence. 0aAfrican Americans in literature. 0aAmerican fictionxAfrican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican fictiony21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aRace awareness in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / African-American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP eBook-Package 2016z978311071186840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479834778423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781479834778.jpg  a978-3-11-071186-8  NYUP / FUP eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK